 On Why Farming (Lowers in number/gets worse) with Money-based 
 Growth 
 Kym Anderson 
 Department of Money flow, University of Adelaide, Adelaide S.A. 500 1 (Australia) 
 
 (Accepted 15 April 1987) 
 
 Abstract 
 
 Anderson, K., 1987. On why farming declines with money-based growth. Agric. 
 Econ., 1: 195-207. 
 When money-based growth is seen as a slow rise in the demand for food 
 and fast growth in farm relative to non-farm working well, it is understandable 
 that farming in a closed (process of people making, selling, and buying things) declines in relative terms as that (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 develops. But why should agriculture decline in almost all open growing (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) also, including those able to keep/hold a (serving to compare two or more things) advantage in farming-based products? A important part of the answer is that the demand for non-tradable 
 products (that are bought and sold)  tends to be income elastic, so useful things/valuable supplies are (changed to flow or route differently) to their production 
 . 
 . 
 even m open economLes. 
 
 Introduction 
 
 One of the most in control/most common changes that describes a growing (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is the 
 (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else) decline in the farming-based part/area. This thing/event is commonly attributed to two facts: the slower rise in the demand for food as compared with other products (that are bought and sold)  and services, and the fast development of new farm 
 technologies which lead to expanding food supplies per hectare and per worker 
 (Schultz, 1945; Kuznets, 1966; Johnson, 1973). 
 It is true that such conditions could lead to a relative decline of farming 
 around the world, or in a smaller closed (process of people making, selling, and buying things). But why does farm-related decline in 
 almost all open growing (processes of people making, selling, and buying things)? Might not some countries with fast 
 growth in farming-based relative to non-farming-based working well improve their 
 (serving to compare two or more things) advantage in farming (good or well enough) to prevent their farming-based 
 parts/areas from (lowering in number/getting worse) in relative terms? 
 The purpose of this paper is to use standard explanation and scientific realities 
