 The measured rates of decline in agriculture's importance would be even faster 
 were it not for the fact that poor countries tend to underprice farming-based products while high-income countries tend to overprice them. 
 Reasons for agriculture's relative decline 
 Republican(s) share 
 
 To understand why farming declines, it is simplest to go ahead in stages, 
 beginning with the GD P share. Think about/believe first the worldwide (or a closed) (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 producing with available useful things/valuable supplies only two final products (that are bought and sold), food (F) from the 
 farming-based part/area and non-food manufactures (M) from the rest of the (process of people making, selling, and buying things). If AB in Fig. 1 represents the production possibility edge of something/unexplored area for the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) in the first period and U a consumption (not caring) curve, then tangency 
 point E will be the point of balance where supply equals demand for both 
 products (that are bought and sold). The balance price ratio is the slope of price line 1. 
 Suppose that with money-based growth the production possibility curve moves 
 out equi-(along with something else/related to something else). Then because the income ability to stretch of demand for 
 food is less than one (Engel's Law), the new balance pointE' will be to 
 the southeast of the ray OE extended and the new price line 2 will be steeper 
 
 198 
 
 than price line 1 (assuming, as is reasonable, that the move/change in the production 
 possibility curve is not only due to population growth, so that per person income 
 rises). That is, the ratio of food to non-food production falls and so too does 
 the ratio of food to non-food prices. Because of this agriculture's share of GDP must 
 fall as a result of this pattern of money-based growth (where GDP is the summed 
 product of price and amount for the two parts/areas in this simple model with no 
 intermediate inputs). 
 If non-food manufactured products (that are bought and sold)  are the numeraire and pis the price of food 
 in terms of manufactures, then from Fig. 1 gross domestic product in this model 
 increases from Fp + M to F'p' + M', where ' points to/shows the new amounts and 
 price ratio. Since M/F &amp;lt; M' /F' andp&amp;gt; p', agriculture's share ofGDP decreases 
 from Fp/ (Fp+ M) to F'p' / (F'p' + M') or, equally, from 1/ (1 + M/Fp) 
 to 1/ (1 + M' /F'p'). 
 Under what facts or conditions (that surround someone) would the GDP share of this (process of people making, selling, and buying things)'s food part/area expand with money-based growth? There are two extreme possibilities, both 
 shown in Fig. 1. One involves working well growth being heavily (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) in favour 
 of non-food, as with a move/change to E"; the other involves the opposite extreme 
 condition, as at E "'. In both cases the part/areaal working well bias has to be (good or well enough) extreme for the effect on the price ratio to more than offset the opposite effect on relative amounts ofF and M. In terms of Fig. 1, the pointE" 
 and the slope of price line 3 would need to be such that M/Fp&amp;gt; M" /F"p". 
 Since M/F &amp;lt; M' /F' &amp;lt; M" /F", a very large increase in the price of food relative 
 to non-food- that is, a very skewed move/change in the production possibility curve 
 in favour of non-food- would be needed/demanded to prevent agriculture's share of 
 GDP from falling as this (process of people making, selling, and buying things) grows. Even if there were to be no working well growth in farming, it is still possible that the skewed effect of income 
 growth on demand could outweigh the skewed effect of working well growth on 
 supply so that the price of food relative to non-food, and because of this agriculture's 
 share of GDP, falls in this growing worldwide (or closed) (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 The other extreme case, atE"', seems even less likely: if growth were to be 
 (good or well enough) (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) in favour of the food part/area to secure/make sure of a new balance at 
 E 0 on the ray OE extended, for example, so that the relative amounts ofF and 
 M produced were the same as at E, the lower relative price of food at E 0 would 
 still secure/make sure of a drop in the food part/area's share of GDP. That is, E "' has to be even 
 further to the northwest corner of Fig. 1 than E 0 - 
 Two reasons can be given as to why an result such as E"' is unlikely. One 
 is that since farming usually is the more labour-intensive part/area of a developing country, the collection of capital per worker as money-based growth go aheads will tend to encourage (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) ofthe more capital-intensive part/area at 
 the expense of the more labour-intensive part/area. This is a standard trade true idea due to Rybczynski (1955). The second reason is based on an scientific 
 (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement). While the evidence on the long-run (popular thing/general way things are going) in the price 
 of first (or most important) products relative to manufactures is still subject to debate, partie- 
 
