 The above model is appropriate for the world (process of people making, selling, and buying things) as a whole, and for a 
 closed national (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Think about/believe now a small country in an open (world-wide process of people making, selling, and buying things), with again only two parts/areas producing the tradable products F and M. 
 Suppose that money-based growth in the rest of the world is not strongly (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) 
 against farming, so the international price of food relative to manufactures 
 is falling as Fig. 2 suggests. If there is no growth in this small country then the 
 decline (in other countries) in the relative price of food from p to p' will result in a 
 decline in the share of farming in this (process of people making, selling, and buying things)'s GDP. This is clear from 
 the movement from E to E' in Fig. 3, since both the price and the amount of 
 food relative to manufactures fall. 
 What if this small (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is also growing? If its growth is such that the 
 production possibility curve moves out equi-(along with something else/related to something else), then agriculture's share of GDP must still (lower in number/get worse). This is because in Fig. 3 F" /M" would 
 then equal F' /M' ( &amp;lt;F/M) and, since p' is still the ruling international and 
 domestic price ratio, it follows that 1/ (1 + M/Fp) &amp;gt; 1 (1 + M" /F"p'). Only if 
 the move/change in this country's production possibility curve is skewed in favour of 
 farming, such as from AB to A"' B"', would it be possible for the increase in 
 production of food relative to manufactures to more than offset the decrease 
 in the relative price of food. 
 Three points are this way worth stressing so far. First, in a growing world (process of people making, selling, and buying things) (or a closed national (process of people making, selling, and buying things)) agriculture's share of total product is 
 likely to (lower in number/get worse) because the income ability to stretch of demand for food is less than 
 one. Only if the (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) in production possibilities is heavily too nice tos 
 non-farming is it possible that the price of food relative to other products (that are bought and sold)  will 
 rise - and even then this price change may not be (good) enough to offset the 
 opposite change in relative production levels and in that way increase agriculture's 
 share of total product. Second, in a small open (process of people making, selling, and buying things) faced with a decline 
 in the relative price of food because of money-based growth in other places, agriculture's share of GDP will fall unless growth in this (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) in favour 
 of farming (unlike for the world (process of people making, selling, and buying things) as a whole). The pro-farming-based 
 bias in its growth (or in its price distortions - see below, "some qualifications") would have to be greater for agriculture's share of national product not 
 to (lower in number/get worse), the larger the fall in the relative price of food (in other countries). And 
 third, the pattern ofdomestic consumption in this model with only two tradable products (that are bought and sold)  is not relevap.t in deciding/figuring out the production pattern in the small 
 open (process of people making, selling, and buying things), again in contrast to the situation for the world (process of people making, selling, and buying things) as a 
 whole; however, as will become clear below, domestic consumption does affect 
 the trade pattern. 
 In reality, a large part of each (process of people making, selling, and buying things) involves the production and con- 
 
 201 
 
 sumption of non-tradable products (that are bought and sold)  and services ( N). These are items for which 
 the costs of overcoming (blocking things) to trading (in other countries) (especially transport costs) are way, way too expensive. If it can be shown that the share of 
 tradables in GDP declines with money-based growth, then this increases the chance even more that agriculture's share of GDP will (lower in number/get worse) in growing 
 (processes of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 To examine this possibility, combine the F and M parts/areas into a super-part/area 
 of tradables, T. The price ofT for our small open (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is given by the 
 international prices ofF and M. The price of non-tradables (N), however, is 
 figured out by/decided by domestic demand and supply conditions because, in balance, domestic demand for non-tradables has to equal domestic supply. 
 Given that the non-tradables part/area is roughly equal to the services 
 part/area (some services are tradable but some products (that are bought and sold)  are non-tradable), and that 
 services make up about one-third of expense in poor countries 
 and two-thirds in high-income countries, it is reasonable to assume that the 
 income ability to stretch of demand for non-tradables goes beyond one, and so the corresponding ability to stretch for all tradables (including food) is less than one. [_( Lluch 
 et al. (1977, table 3.12) received/got guesses of expense elasticities in the 
 range 1.3-1.8 for major groups of services. More recent thin sliceal studies 
 support the expectation of an income ability to stretch of demand for services of well 
 above togetherness for poor countries but slowly approaching togetherness as countries get richer ( Kravis et al., 1983; Summers, 1985).] 
 Figure 1 can be used to illustrate what happens when a small open (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 with a tradables part/area grows, if on the axes F is replaced by T and M by N. 
 Then E is the first balance point (when demand for and supply of nontradables are equated) and price line 1 represents the first price of nontradables relative to tradables. Now assume the price ofT remains unchanged 
 for the moment but there is money-based growth which moves/changes out the production 
 possibility curve. If the curve moves out equiproportionately from AB to A' B' 
 then necessarily both the price and amount of non-tradables relative to tradables must increase (a real exchange rate appreciation), given that E' must 
 be to the southeast of the ray OE extended because of the income effect. That 
 is, tradables add/give a (lowering in number/getting worse) proportion of GDP in an (process of people making, selling, and buying things) whose 
 working well growth is not part/areaally (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) but whose consumption growth 
 pattern is (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) against tradables. 
 As with the earlier discussion of the (world-wide process of people making, selling, and buying things) without non-tradables, 
 there are two extreme sets of conditions in which, mentally, the nontradables part/area of a growing (process of people making, selling, and buying things) would not expand its share of GDP. One 
 is represented by point E", the other by E "'. To reach E", growth would have 
 to be heavily (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) in favour of non-tradables production and the ability to stretch of 
 substitution in consumption between T and N low for the relative price of nontradables to fall (good or well enough) to offset the increase in production of non-tradables relative to tradables. Or, to reach E"' growth would have to be 
 
 202 
 
 heavily (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) in favour of tradables production and again the ability to stretch of 
 substitution in consumption between T and N low for the relative price ofnontradables to rise (good or well enough) to offset the decrease in production of non-tradables relative to tradables. The first possibility seems most unlikely, given that 
 working well growth has, if anything, been (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) against the non-tradables 
 part/area (Clark, 1957). The second possibility is less remote, but recall that it 
 needs/demands an extreme bias in working well growth against non-tradables to offset 
 the consumption bias in favour of tradables: it is not (good) enough, for example, 
 to be only (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) enough for point E 0 to be reached. 
 So, since agriculture's share ofthe tradables part ofGDP is likely to (lower in number/get worse), 
 and the tradables' share of GDP is also likely to fall, introducing a non-tradables part/area into the model to make it more closely represent a real (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 makes it even more likely that agriculture's share of GDP will (lower in number/get worse) with 
 money-based growth. 
 Employment share 
 
 The above thinking is also (good) enough for explaining the decline in agriculture's share of employment, except in cases where farming-based labour working well grows very slowly relative to labour working well in other parts/areas. 
 Where labour working well is growing more quickly on farms than in non-farm 
 jobs, as appears to have been the case in industrial countries during recent 
 20 years (Table 1) , there is even more reason to expect farming to become 
 a less important employer. In fact, the number of people employed on farms in 
 industrial countries has (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) totally, the rate of decline averaging 2.8% 
 per year during the period 1960-1981 (Organisation for Money-based Cooperation and Development, 1983). 
 Export share 
 
 Why is agriculture's share of exports less strongly related to per person 
 income than is agriculture's share of GDP or employment, as shown in the 
 above moving backward equations? Think about/believe again a small (process of people making, selling, and buying things) within an open 
 (world-wide process of people making, selling, and buying things) in which the international price of food relative to other tradables is (lowering in number/getting worse) over time because working well growth in the rest of the world 
 is not strongly enough (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) against farming to offset the effect of a relative 
 decline in food demand. If this small (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is not growing, then clearly the 
 share of farming in exports will (lower in number/get worse): the price change would discourage 
 domestic food production and encourage domestic food consumption, while the 
 opposite would happen in the domestic market for non-foods. If this small (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is growing and if its working well growth is part/areaally fair, then this 
 habit/desire for agriculture's share of exports to fall would be weakened because 
 domestic demand would grow less quickly for food than for non-food. And it 
 
 203 
 
 would be weakened further if working well growth grew faster in farming 
 than non-farming in this small (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 This way it is understandable that the share of farming in exports is less 
 strongly (negatively) related to per person income than agriculture's 
 shares of GDP and employment. A negative relationship anyway is likely, 
 both for (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) which are growing only slowly and, especially, for (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) where working well growth is fastest in the industrial part/area; a positive 
 relationship will happen only for those (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) where working well growth in 
 farming is (good or well enough) greater than in manufacturing to be able to 
 create added/more food export amounts/quantities to more than offset the long-term 
 decline in the real international price of food. Note, however, that a declining 
 (thing that's given/work that's done) to the country's exports from farming does not necessarily suggest 
 a (lowering in number/getting worse) farming-based (serving to compare two or more things) advantage as showed by the pattern of 
 its export (focusing on doing one thing very well). This is because agriculture's importance in world trade 
 may be falling even faster than its importance in this country's exports. 
 Some qualifications 
 
 The above discussion has (thought about (or related to) ideas and possibilities) from the fact that many (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 seriously distort (rewards or reasons for doing something) faced by producers and people. Especially, 
 it is common for poor (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) to tax farming relative to manufacturing, for high-income (especially food-shortage) (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) to give money to farming relative to manufacturing, and for growing (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) to slowly 
 change from the former to the last thing just mentioned as they industrialise. [See, for example, 
 Little et al. (1970), Balassa et al. (1971), Anderson and Hayami (1986) and 
 Tyers and Anderson (in press). The last thing just mentioned two studies also suggest reasons for 
 the growth of farming-based protection in industrialising countries.] Any one 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) following this pattern after having taxed farming would slow the 
 pace of decline of its farming-based part/area, both because of the direct effect of 
 price changes on part/areaal output levels and on their changing per unit (putting a value on something) at twisted/partially untrue/lied about domestic prices, and because ofthe indirect effect those changes 
 have in boosting investments in new farm technology. In fact the last thing just mentioned can be 
 large enough to actually reverse the (process of people making, selling, and buying things)'s net food trade position, as has 
 been the case in Western Europe and China during the last few years. When many 
 (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) obey this distortions pattern (at the same time), the effect on 
 international food prices depends on the proportion of world food markets that 
 is low priced as compared with the proportion that is high priced. Over time, 
 however, as each (process of people making, selling, and buying things) industrialises and so moves towards the farming-based 
 protection camp, the net effect will be to add to the downward pressure on the 
 international price of food relative to other tradables. As a result, the farming-based part/area of (clear and appearing as it should/without any changes from the truth)  (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) will be under pressure to (lower in number/get worse) even 
 faster than would be the case in a distortion-free world. 
