 percentage of value added rather than of total value of production. This would 
 not matter if the value-added share of output was constant or changed at the 
 same rate in each part/area. But, as Table 2 shows, that share has been declining 
 much more quickly in farming than in manufacturing: during the twenty years to 1983, the share for industrial countries (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) from 48 to 39% for 
 farming but only from 40 to 38% for manufacturing, measured at domestic 
 prices. [The relative decline in agriculture's share would have been even greater 
 if measured at international prices, given the gradual growth in farming-based 
 protection talked about/said above.] This adds to the reasons for the decline in agriculture's share of GDP. The second change is to think about  the part/areaal 
 source of (middle-position) products (that are bought and sold)  and services. Casual scientificism suggests the nonfarm parts/areas usually/(in the past) have supplied a surprisingly more large and 
 
 205 
 
 increasing share of those inputs, so this again strengthens the expectation of 
 a decline in agriculture's share of GDP. 
 Throughout, the discussion has used the term food to describe farming-based 
 output. While non-food farming-based products are (a) little different in that the 
 income ability to stretch of demand for them is not necessarily below one and falling, 
 they are (compared to other things) small contributors to total farming-based output, so the ends/end results are unlikely to be changed if they had been specifically included in the 
 analysis. 
 End/end result 
 
 This analysis allows the following ends/end results to be drawn. First, in a growing world (process of people making, selling, and buying things) (or a closed national (process of people making, selling, and buying things)), agriculture's shares of 
 GDP and employment are likely to (lower in number/get worse) because the income ability to stretch of 
 demand for food is less than one; to avoid this would require a heavy bias in 
 working well growth towards the non-farm part/area. A result/resulting/statement is that the world 
 price of food relative to non-food is likely to (lower in number/get worse) with worldwide  money-based 
 growth. 
 Second, in a small open (process of people making, selling, and buying things) faced with a decline in the relative price of 
 food because of money-based growth in other places, agriculture's shares of GDP, 
 employment and exports are likely to (lower in number/get worse). This is so even if this small 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is itself not growing, because of the decline in international food prices. 
 If it is growing, then agriculture's shares of GDP and employment, if not of 
 exports, are even more likely to (lower in number/get worse) because of the low domestic income 
 ability to stretch of demand for food. To avoid (lowering in number/getting worse) needs/demands either a strong bias 
 in working well growth towards the farm part/area (in contrast with the worldwide  or 
 closed (process of people making, selling, and buying things) case) and/ or a heavy distortion of (rewards or reasons for doing something) towards farm-related. Experience hints that even then the decline in agriculture's shares of 
 GDP and employment are unlikely to be arrested: Western Europe and China 
 provide recent examples of reversing the downward (popular thing/general way things are going) in agriculture's share 
 of exports, but not GDP and employment, through price policy changes which 
 improved (rewards or reasons for doing something) for farmers. 
 Third, the fact that many countries tend to distort (rewards or reasons for doing something) more and more 
 in favour of farmers as their (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) industrialise, which further depresses 
 the real international price of food, only adds to the chance of farming 
 declining in (clear and appearing as it should/without any changes from the truth)  (processes of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 Finally, it should be stressed that it does not follow from this analysis that 
 farmers necessarily lose from money-based growth. Part of the reason for declining 
 real food prices is increased working well on farms, and part of the reason for 
 labour moving out of farming is improved income-earning prospects in nonfarm parts/areas. So farm families may well be sharing in the fruits of money-based growth either through new farm technologies which raise farm labour 
 and land working well and/or through household members taking higher-pay- 
 
 206 
 
 ing jobs in other parts/areas. Nor does it follow that policies should be put into use to 
 speed up useful thing/valuable supply movements away from the (lowering in number/getting worse) farming-based part/area. On 
 the opposite, the policy response (fought for/pleaded for) by Prebisch (1964) and others to 
 declining terms of trade for countries exporting first (or most important) products, namely, protecting the import-competing manufacturing part/area to (change to flow on a different path/change to point to, or focus on, something else) useful things/valuable supplies 
 away from first (or most important) production, would only make things worse for farmers and 
 the total (process of people making, selling, and buying things), as it would worsen the domestic terms of trade for nonmanufacturing parts/areas as well as reduce national income and because of this non-farm 
 job prospects for farm household members. 
 
